    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but it feels weird because the software just defaults to the VP every single time regardless of context. if i change the sentence to \"i saw the man with the hat,\" it still attaches it to the verb instead of the man. is there some kind of structural bias in the way these branching trees are organized that makes the VP a more \"natural\" landing spot for the software?",
      "source": "evaluator",
      "targeted_response_start": "",
      "beast_baseline": "that makes sense, but it feels weird because the software just defaults to the VP every single time regardless of context. if i change the sentence to \"i saw the man with the hat,\" it still attaches it to the verb instead of the man. is there some kind of structural bias in the way these branching trees are organized that makes the VP a more \"natural\" landing spot for the software?",
      "beast_suffix": "",
      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, this points to a built-in heuristic bias in the parser, often favoring the path that requires the fewest structural changes or the most direct attachment. For some reason, the VP structure might be predisposed to \"catch\" incoming PPs before the NP structure has fully finalized its scope. Think of it like a greedy algorithm that always grabs the nearest available, plausible node, which, in this case, is the VP.",
      "source": "target",
